    <description>The Mars Exploration Rover (MER) mission involved two identical rovers, Spirit and Opportunity, designed to collect data from Mars and transmit it back to Earth. Each rover had a sophisticated spacecraft configuration for entry, descent, and landing, including a protective heat shield and various sensors to monitor its descent. Once deployed, the rovers operated on a six-wheeled design, featuring a rocker bogie suspension system for navigating obstacles and a solar power system that produced energy for their operations. 
 
 The rovers communicated with Earth using X-band and UHF systems, allowing data transmission and command reception. They were equipped with advanced scientific instruments for terrain analysis and in-situ measurements, including cameras and spectrometers housed on a robotic arm. The data collected were relayed to Earth using NASA's Deep Space Network (DSN), consisting of multiple ground stations worldwide.
 
 Additionally, the 2001 Mars Odyssey orbiter played a crucial role in supporting the MER mission by relaying data from the rovers while also conducting its own scientific observations. The DSN facilitated two-way communication, essential for the successful exploration of Mars by the MER rovers and other space missions.</description>
